segments.text: who has been with the College of Education since before it was a college of education.

And he's going to share some of his perceptions of things that have occurred and changes that have come about in the college, and what might have created some of them, and where we are, where we might be going.
So starting with the beginning, you came?
I came to A&M in 1961.
OK.
as a counselor in the Counseling Testing Service and a part-time assistant professor of psychology in the then Department of Education and Psychology, as it was known at that time.
I taught part-time there until 1969.

when the College of Education was formed out of the Department of Education, the departments, Ag Education, Industrial Education, Health and Physical Education, curriculum instruction and stuff like that.
And I became an associate professor of educational psychology at that time and associate dean of the new college.
under W.R. Hubert.
What were your duties as Associate Dean?
Associate Dean for Student Personnel Services.
Is that what Brian Cole is right now?
That's right.
And Dr. Limbacher was?
Dr. Limbacher was that before him.
And then you were before Limbacher?
I was the first one, yeah.
And I was that for two years.
But I wrote the proposal for the, I should say I finished writing the proposal presented to the Coordinating Board in Austin for formation of the College of Education.
Oh, I see.
I have a copy of that.
The proposal.
And I presented it.
It all happened pretty fast.
It wasn't a long drawn out thing, right?
Right.
Dean Frank W.R. Hubert in 1961 was dean of the College of Arts and Science, Texas A&M University.
And then he split off from that college, the College of Business, the College of Science, the College of Geoscience, the College of Liberal Arts, and the College of Education.
One by one, he split those away, and of course he, being an educator, chose to keep the College of Education.
It changed and happened as the college began to evolve.
Always, though, the mission has still remained the teaching, the research, and the service.
In your opinion, has that changed drastically in focus from the Hubert era to the Corrigan era or in between?
No, I don't think it's changed.
Our emphasis on the preparation of teachers still has always been there.
Search and service has been carried on in many different ways.
There was a laboratory for human learning in the Department of Education and Psychology which moved over to the Department of Psychology.
There was a human learning laboratory which was and still is over in the
of health and physical education.
Of course, that emphasis was on physical performance instead of intellectual performance of students.
I don't know what else.
Now, go ahead.
OK. One of the things that I have been talking about with different department people is how this growth and these changes have affected your ability to work with students.
In graduate programs, it's not as pronounced as it is in the undergraduate level as far as the growth, because this department has been pretty stable as far as growth, right?
I mean, there's a limit to the growth here in this department, whereas there is not that in some others.
Well, within this department now, when you get off the College of Education and begin to talk about the department itself, there have been some rather drastic changes.
At one time, we spent about 90% of our time
in terms of courses and professors preparing people to be special education chief counselors and school counselors.
Later they added school psychologists to the preparation, but the preparation of school counselors has decreased over the years.
probably less than 10% of our department is concerned with preparation of school counselors.
And we are now concerned with the preparation of school psychologists, special education teachers, and independently practicing psychologists and researchers at the PhD level.
This has been a change from the early days when we were almost all school counseling.
Do you see a lot of collaboration, or has there been a lot of collaboration, not only within the department, but among departments in the college?
Well, we've always had some joint appointments.
Several people had joint appointments between curriculum instruction and educational psychology.
We now have
joint appointments with the Student Counseling Service and the Department of Educational Psychology.
And we now have some... By joint appointments?
Not exactly joint appointments.
Both people are listed as adjunct professors.
Some that are working in the counseling?
They're working full-time in the student counseling service, but they teach a course for us.
Oh, I see.
OK. And likewise, with a couple of local psychiatrists who are listed as adjunct professors in the department.
We've never had that before.
And we now have that where we'll have people off campus doing work with campus in terms of research and service.
If you're talking about the department also, then you'd have to talk about one major aspect of it, which is the Student Counseling Service.
I don't mean Student Counseling Service, I mean the Counseling and Assessment Clinic.
We have here on the seventh floor in connection with the department.
This is in effect a teaching laboratory, but one which takes referrals from
physicians and counselors and psychologists and progression workers within 150 or 200 miles of campus for special workups.
All of the work being done by our students and supervised by a licensed psychologist so that in effect it is a miniature mental health facility.
When did that come about?
It came about in 1972, I believe, and began to use the laboratory as it was set up in this building.
This building was designed mostly by, I think, by Dean Hubert.
And the teaching laboratories, the science teaching laboratories, counseling laboratories, reading laboratories,
all designed into the basic building structure.
And when we moved into the building in 1973, that's when the laboratory began.
Where is that located, up here somewhere?
On the seventh floor.
Okay.
Do you have some perceptions on how outsiders view the College of Education in general?
Not just outsiders meaning the other colleges, but even beyond that.
By outsiders you mean other professional educators or laymen?
Other, well, either or both.
Outside educators see it as a sort of a

this kind of thing, because I think that it's a little bit harder to get into and to finish teacher training, counselor training, and whatever at this institution, which may be a reflection of the institution more than it is of the College of Education in particular.
That's the way some professional people might see it.
Lay people around the country, how do they see it?
We have our practice teachers in all kinds of schools from Fort Worth to Houston.
To San Antonio.
And San Antonio.
That doesn't particularly concern just the department here.
It concerns the whole College of Education.
There have been some efforts to do basic research through various school districts.
from school districts that I'm aware of.
We also taught some off-campus courses for years and we finally got out of this business.
We taught off-campus courses in Galveston and San Tom and Houston and El Paso and Amarillo and Waco that I can remember right now.
Why was that discontinued?
For economic reasons and political reasons, as far as I can tell, they didn't want us competing unfairly with the local campuses there.
I taught courses in Galveston where I traveled out one night a week and talked to teachers and others from the local school districts down there.
I thought it was good educational experience for those people who wanted to
get credit in this university, but they could not afford to travel up here.
The argument against it was that they didn't have access to the library, and to a position with other professors and other graduate students.
But I think this was overcome some by the fact that they were all professionals teaching in the field.
And at the same time, they were getting a course.
They were practicing their profession at the same time.
OK. What about your crystal ball for the future?
Do you have some?
Well, let me mention one other community project.
Three years ago, the Houston School District had a lack of Latin American
counselors in the system.
And there was a joint contract between HISD and the Department of Education and Psychology, College of Education, to prepare.
And we took 24 classroom teachers and in two years time we gave them our counseling curriculum and everything.
And the counselors finished our program here.
The HISD paid a lot of their expenses.
Books, tuition, stuff like that.
So it has some minority counselors in the Houston system.
All those people have upheld the high traditions of the department in terms of subsequent productivity, jobs, promotion, stuff like that.
I was really an example of the kind of cooperation, I think, that a college or university campus can have on their local students.
By the way, some of those courses were taught off campus.
All the courses in San Antonio, myself?
Yes.
Okay.
Do you think there's going to be great changes in the very near future?
I know this new Bill 994 is going to affect a lot of the undergraduate teacher cooperation.
How do you feel about that?
What does the future bode for us?
A few years back, they predicted a huge overage of teachers to be a false prediction because there was a shortage instead of an overage of teachers.
Because not only did we hit the second generation of baby boomers, but because a lot of people in the teaching profession became disenchanted and left the teaching profession.
So that's what caused the shortage in the
the last three years.

As we move into the era of smaller class size, not only at the elementary level, but at some of the upper levels, I think there will be more demand for teachers and counselors, especially education teachers.
As you know, this department has an experimental program six years in length
in which we prepare special education teachers who will finish the six years with a master's degree, certification, and one year's internship type experience in public schools.
That's almost close to what the proposal is going to be for the new five year program.
Yeah.
Well, this will be a six-year program, and you'd have to go to Doug Palmer to get the full description of that.
You already have it in place, or you're looking at it?
No, it's in place.
That's the only way we sign up, special education people.
And you may want to talk to Dr. Palmer briefly about that, that special education program, that six-year program.
Okay.
All of them are in that six-year program, all special ed people then?
All of them.
We enroll from now on.
Oh, from now on.
From now on.
Okay.
We're getting the fall of it, 87.
Okay.
Dr. Hope, what about some of the highlights, and you've gone through a lot of things and a lot of changes and so forth, and you've contributed a lot.
Can you share some insights or maybe an anecdote or two?
What do you feel the best about what you've done since you've been at Texas A&M?
Down through the years?
Right.
Well, when I was a part-time professor and a full-time counselor over in the Counseling and Testing Center, Mm-hmm.
We were charged with doing the research which convinced the board and the constituents to become coeducational.
We did a survey of the surrounding communities to find out how many women would come to Texas A&M if they had the opportunity and could not go anywhere else.
Who gave you that charge?
President Rutter.
then President Rudder.

We also, as a part of our work there, the research part of our work there, we were given the charge to examine the distribution of grants from the National Science Foundation to the various colleges and universities of the United States.
And that study was taken to Washington by
Congressman Teague and used to cause a lot more grants to come the way of Texas A&M.
I'm talking now about science and technology.
That study we did at President Rutter's request.
One of the first things we did was initiate the use of the Scholastic Attitude Test for admission purposes to the university.
That was my first job here in 1961, was to do a validating study of the SAT and the students in the university at that time.
I think one of the most exciting things was that they predicted that as we raised our entrance requirements, that is, SAT and graduate school grade point ratio, that we would cut the
size of the freshman class.
Well, this happened for perhaps one year, maybe 1963.
Then from then on, instead of having fewer students, we had more and more students of higher quality.
Do you think that's going to continue now that we've raced it yet again?
Yes, it will continue in my opinion.
College of Business had the same experience with the GRE.
And we were given the job also of administering the GRE to every graduating senior at A&M and doing a validation study for it.
And it was this, and that was 1965, 4 or 5, somewhere along in there.
We didn't even require the GRE for graduate school until much later than that.
With that information, the president went out and began to beef up the departments that showed low scores on achievement.
And he began to draw attention to those that had high scores on achievements.
The president or the dean?
The president.
She asked me about the whole university, and that's why we didn't have a college of education in those days.
That's true, that's right.
You also worked, I'm dividing my study I think into the two eras, the Hubert era and the Corrigan era.
Can you tell me a little bit about the
the contrast in the two.
I know there's been a lot, I mean, I've gotten a lot on the different leadership styles and so forth.
Do you have any, you know, a certain observation on that?
Dean Hubert seemed to keep his touch at all times to all facets of the college operation.

This is not to say that he was not flexible in any way whatsoever, but he knew an awful lot about what was going on at a departmental level, and he took responsibility for directing some of that work.
My perception of Dean Kurgan, while I wasn't in the office with Dean Kurgan, is that he is more likely to give a general charge
to a department or a facet within the college of education and leave the execution of that to them.
I would say that you'd have to say that both deans were intimately involved in the statewide scene.
Frank Hubert, before he became dean of Texas A&M, was in the Texas Education Agency itself.
had an intimate knowledge of the functioning inside that thing.
After Dean Kurgan came, he was on the governor's select committee and he was deeply involved in the suggestions which led to the law.
You'd have to say that Texas A&M, the deans of education for the past
have been very active in the state scene about what's happening to education.
Which has been beneficial to the College of Education office.
Right.
Okay.
In closing, do you have any remarks or anything that you would be helpful in for me to kind of tie all those little ends together as to looking at the- The history of the College of Education.
Well, if you went way back, you'd find that the first education courses were taught in ag education.
You may be aware of that.
The first psychology course was taught in 1916 in the department of rural sociology, I believe.
And one considers that the first college courses in the whole United States were only taught
We had a course here in 1916 that indicated we had some forward looking people.
Are you still full-time or are you semi-retired now?
No, I'm taking early retirement and I'm what we call a half-time person now.
I had 25 years, 26 years here and half-time in September.
What are you doing with your other half-time?
Oh, I work a little bit for Greenleaf Psychiatric Hospital, where we have a lot of our students and faculty working in the mental health area.
And we do a lot of work there.
Okay.
That's an unofficial remark, of course.
Well, I appreciate your time and your perceptions and your insights and
you've made me aware of some things that I was not aware of as far as, you know, studies and things and how they came about.
And do you have anything that you have written yourself?
I mean, have you ever recorded any of your, you know, thoughts?
No, we did an informal Phi Delta Kappa a few years back when we organized the chapter.
Had a little research grant for Dr. Barker and Dr. McCandless and I in which we looked at, you know,
incidents of male elementary school teachers.
Because we felt like one of the facts we had was a male figure for elementary school children to identify with.
And of course we documented with that little study the fact that there was a huge preponderance of females
elementary level, even in the principal's office.
There was a huge group of hundreds of females in that office.
And I contrast this as only a slight change from the times when not only were you supposed to be female to teach elementary school,
If you got married, you had to quit.
Especially if you got married and got pregnant, you had to quit teaching.
Well, there's a little bit of change over the years with respect to that.
I also did a study for Southwest Athletic Conference as part of my faculty response military where we studied prediction of grade point ratios for the whole university in order to set standards
And in this respect we studied all males, not just male athletes, at the nine Southwest Conference schools.
And it was with this study that we demonstrated the usable qualities as far as SAT and grade point ratio are concerned of the various schools.
Have you done any of your memoirs of anything?
No.
Never?
I have not.
Are you going to now that you have all this time?
That's a good thought.
I've had some experience.
I think you should.
You know, one of the reasons I...
I hope I can finish this.
I do thank you for your time, and I hope if I have some questions I can come back.
